@flexiarg equity/ARGUMENT
@title Argument for the Equity Pattern Domain
@keywords equity, capability, governance, commons, contribution, loop, Sen, Ostrom, Alexander, Mehaffy, NPT
@audience futon developers, programme designers, theory reviewers
@tone analytic-foundational
@style argument
@references [equity/confident-adaptation equity/protected-interaction equity/shared-maintenance equity/contribution-pathways equity/visible-impact]

@summary A collective production system is equitable when contribution,
governance, and capability expansion form one loop: doing the work
increases stake, stake increases recognised scope to shape the system,
and that governance in turn enlarges participants' real capability to
contribute and benefit.  When those elements decouple, the system
becomes brittle, stagnant, or extractive.  This domain contains five
patterns derived from a qualitative evaluation of the UKRN Open
Research Programme (Train-the-Trainer model), analysed through
Normalisation Process Theory and interpreted using Sen (capability),
Ostrom (commons governance), and Alexander/Mehaffy (pattern-language
method).  The five patterns form a coordination gradient: each
requires progressively more actors and longer chains to resolve.

! argument:

  == PART I: The Equity Loop ==

  E1. [Evidence: equity.tex, theoretical synthesis]
  Three inputs — Sen's capability approach, Ostrom's commons
  governance, and Alexander's pattern-language method — reduce to a
  single design criterion: does this system close the loop between
  contribution, governance, and capability?

  E2. [Evidence: equity.tex, five diagnostic questions]
  The criterion decomposes into five questions:
  1. Contribution: What kinds of labour keep the system alive?
  2. Recognition: How does doing that work create legitimate stake?
  3. Governance: What rights do contributors have to shape the system?
  4. Capability: How does participation enlarge real opportunity to act?
  5. Feedback: What mechanisms show whether the loop is working?

  E3. [Evidence: equity.tex, failure modes table]
  Six ways the loop breaks: contribution without governance (extraction),
  governance without capability expansion (performative), capability
  without shared stake (training for exit), governance without
  contribution (managerial), contribution without feedback (motivation
  decay), local adaptation without shared stewardship (fragmentation).

  == PART II: The Five Patterns ==

  P1. [Pattern: equity/confident-adaptation]
  Adaptation without clarity is guesswork.
  Equity loop joint: contribution→stake.
  Coordination: Low (1 actor).

  P2. [Pattern: equity/protected-interaction]
  Delivery without provisioning produces overload.
  Equity loop joint: governance→capability.
  Coordination: Medium (2 actors).

  P3. [Pattern: equity/shared-maintenance]
  Local adaptation without stewardship fragments the commons.
  Equity loop joint: capability→contribution.
  Coordination: Medium-high (community).

  P4. [Pattern: equity/contribution-pathways]
  Recipients without voice remain recipients.
  Equity loop joint: contribution→stake→governance.
  Coordination: High (infrastructure).

  P5. [Pattern: equity/visible-impact]
  A programme that cannot see its own effects cannot learn.
  Equity loop joint: feedback (whole loop).
  Coordination: Very high (6+ actor chain).

  == PART III: The Coordination Gradient ==

  The five patterns are not independent recommendations.  They form a
  gradient: each requires more actors, in longer chains, to resolve.
  A programme that addresses patterns 1-3 will improve its training
  input.  A programme that also addresses patterns 4-5 will build the
  institutional architecture needed for that input to persist as
  collective practice.

  The gradient explains why partial success is common: an institution
  that resolves conditions 1-3 but not 4-5 will see good delivery but
  fragile sustainability.  This is not a failure of effort; it is a
  predictable consequence of incomplete institutional architecture.

  == PART IV: Relevance to FUTON ==

  CONCERN: FUTON's own coordination layers face the same equity
  questions.  Do contributors to the pattern library gain recognised
  scope to shape the stack?  Does participation in missions enlarge
  real capability?  Does the glacial loop close the feedback chain?
  Every FUTON layer should be testable against the five diagnostic
  questions from equity.tex.  If the equity loop does not close,
  the layer is extractive regardless of its stated intentions.

  The university case (futon7/holes/M-another-university.md)
  demonstrates what happens when a well-funded programme coordinates
  activities without coordinating the architecture that makes those
  activities productive.  FUTON exists partly because that failure is
  not specific to universities — it is the general form of the problem.

  == THESIS ==

  The five equity patterns specify, in conditional form, what must
  hold for a distributed collective production system to close the
  equity loop.  They were derived from one empirical case but the
  loop they inspect is domain-independent.  The coordination gradient
  they form is a structural prediction: systems that resolve the
  lower-complexity conditions but not the higher-complexity ones will
  produce partial, fragile outcomes — not because participants lack
  motivation, but because the institutional architecture is incomplete.
